,"meanings":["From the Late Latin name <i>Constantinus</i>, a derivative of <i>Constans</i>;  see  Constant .  In early modern English the names <i>Constant</i> and <i>Constantine</i> were not always clearly distinguished. The Roman emperor  Constantine the Great  (  ?288–337 ) is specially honoured in the Christian Church as the first Christian emperor. The name was also borne by three kings of medieval Scotland, where it represents an Anglicized form of the Gaelic name   Conn  , and is a traditional name in the Phipps (Marquesses of Normanby) family."],"variants":[]},{"name":"II","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Violet  ,   Vivien  , or   Vivian ."],"variants":[{"name":"Vivien","meanings":["Earlier generally taken as a variant of the boy's name   Vivian  , but now also rarely used for boys. This spelling was quite common in Old French. Its use as a girl's name in the English-speaking world was influenced by  Tennyson's  Merlin and Vivien (  1859 ). This name, from Arthurian legend, may represent an altered form of a Celtic name (perhaps akin to the Irish Gaelic name <i>Béibhinn</i> ‘white lady’, pronounced ‘bee-<b>veen</b>’). The actress  Vivien Leigh  (  1913–67 ) was christened <i>Vivian</i>."]},{"name":"Violet","meanings":["From the name of the flower (Old French <i>violette</i>, Late Latin <i>violetta</i>, a diminutive of <i>viola</i>). This was one of the earliest flower names to become popular in Britain, being used as early as  1700  and becoming well established in the 19th century, although it is now somewhat out of favour."]},{"name":"Vivian","meanings":["Originally a boy's name, from an Old French form of the Latin name <i>Vivianus</i> (probably a derivative of <i>vivus</i> ‘alive’), but now more frequent as a girl's name. The name was borne by a 5th-century bishop of Saintes in western France, remembered for protecting his people during the invasion of the Visigoths."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1354950,"age":16,"year":"1385","julianDay":2226922,"description":"Sofia captured by Ottoman Empire.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1354951,"age":20,"year":"1389","julianDay":2228383,"description":"Turks defeat Serbs at Kosovo Polje. Exposes the remaining Bulgarian territory to Ottoman occupation.","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"When The Exiled Emperor Constantine II Asen of Bulgaria was born in 1369, in Vidin, Bulgaria, his father, Prince Ivan Stracimirović of Vidin Bulgaria, was 46 and his mother, Anna Slava of Wallachia, was 30. He had at least 1 daughter with Irene Palaiologina Philanthropene. He died on 16 September 1422, in Belgrade, Serbia, at the age of 53."},"et":{"1369–16 September 1422":"1369–16. september 1422","1355–1390":"1355–1390","1358–1422":"1358–1422","1369–1422":"1369–1422","1249–1280":"1249–1280","1380–Female":"1380–Surnud","1400–Female":"1400–Surnud","1382–Female":"1382–Surnud","1324–1396":"1324–1396","1339–1371":"1339–1371","15 Sep 1396":"15. september 1396","1385":"1385","1396":"1396","1371":"1371","1382":"1382","1360":"1360","1380":"1380","1280":"1280","1390":"1390","1249":"1249","1369":"1369","1358":"1358","1324":"1324","1397-1422":"1397 kuni 1422","1389":"1389","1400":"1400","1422":"1422","1355":"1355","about 1400":"umbes 1400","16 September 1422":"16. september 1422","1339":"1339","Vidin, Bulgária":"Vidin, Bulgaaria","Curtea de Argeş, Argeş, Rumänien":"Curtea de Argeş, Argeş, Rumeenia","Romania":"Rumeenia","Belgrade, Serbia":"Belehrad, Serbien","Vidin, Bulgarien":"Vidin, Bulgaaria","Serbia":"Serbien","Bulgaria":"Bulgaaria"},"fi":{"1369–16 September 1422":"1369–16. syyskuuta 1422","1355–1390":"1355–1390","1358–1422":"1358–1422","1369–1422":"1369–1422","1249–1280":"1249–1280","1380–Female":"1380–Kuollut","1400–Female":"1400–Kuollut","1382–Female":"1382–Kuollut","1324–1396":"1324–1396","1339–1371":"1339–1371","15 Sep 1396":"15. syyskuuta 1396","1385":"1385","1396":"1396","1371":"1371","1